      "‖X t ω‖`, and then `hittingAfter f (Set.Ici K) ⊥ ω` is the first time after ⊥ (in ι) where `f t ω ∈ Set.Ici K` (i.e., `‖X t ω‖ ≥ K`). \n\nBut Lean does not have such a function `hittingAfter` in its standard library, so likely the Lean code was meant to use `hittingTime` or `hittingAfter` from some project. \n\nHowever, given the confusion, and since the problem is asking to replace `sorry` and the rest of the Lean code is irrelevant, perhaps we can reason directly from the mathematical inequality without relying on the precise Lean definition of `hittingAfter`. \n\n### Mathematical Analysis of the Inequality\n\nThe inequality is:\n`sup_{s ≤ t} ‖X_s^τ‖ ≤ K + 1_{τ ≤ t} ‖X_τ‖` \nwhere `τ` is the first time after ⊥ (in ι) where `‖X_s‖ ≥ K`, or `⊤` if it never happens, and `X^τ` is the process stopped at `τ`.\n\nBut the Lean code is using `⨆ s, ⨆ (_ : s ≤ t), ‖stoppedProcess X τ s ω‖`, which is the same as `sup_{s ≤ t} ‖X_s^τ‖`. \n\nAssuming that in the case `τ = ⊤`, `X_s^τ = X_s` for all `s`, and if `τ = s₀ ∈ ι`, then `X_s^τ = X_s if s < s₀ else X_{s₀}`. \n\nBut it is unclear whether `hittingAfter` returns `⊤` if `K` is never hit, or `⊥` if it is hit at `⊥`. \n\nBut perhaps we can assume that `τ = hittingAfter ... ⊥` is such that `τ ≥ ⊥`, and if `K` is never hit, then `τ = ⊤`.\n\nThe RHS is `K + 1_{τ ≤ t} ‖X_τ‖`.\n\nSo the inequality is `sup_{s ≤ t} ‖X_s^τ‖ ≤ K + 1_{τ ≤ t} ‖X_τ‖`.\n\nLet's consider cases:\n\n1. **Case `τ = ⊤`**:\n   Then `X_s^τ = X_s` for all `s`, and the LHS is `sup_{s ≤ t} ‖X_s‖`.\n   The RHS is `K + 0` because `τ = ⊤ ≰ t`.\n   But the LHS need not be bounded by `K`. However, perhaps in this case, `‖X_s‖ < K` for all `s`, so `sup_{s ≤ t} ‖X_s‖ < K`, but the RHS is `K`, so the inequality would hold. \n   But this is only true if `τ = ⊤` implies `‖X_s‖ < K` for all `s`, which is likely the case because `τ` is the first time where `≥ K`, and if no such time exists, `τ = ⊤`. \n\n   But this relies on the definition of `hittingAfter`.\n\n2. **Case `τ ∈ ι` (i.e., `τ < ⊤`)**:\n   - If `τ ≤ t`, then for `s ≤ t`, `X_s^τ` is `X_s` if `s < τ` and `X_τ` if `s ≥ τ`.\n     The supremum is `max(sup_{s < τ} ‖X_s‖, ‖X_τ‖)`.\n     But since `τ` is the first time where `‖X_τ‖ ≥ K`, for `s < τ`, `‖X_s‖ < K`.\n     Thus, `sup_{s < τ} ‖X_s‖ < K`, and `‖X_τ‖ ≥ K`, so the LHS is `‖X_τ‖`.\n     The RHS is `K + ‖X_τ‖`, so `‖X_τ‖ ≤ K + ‖X_τ‖`, which is true.\n   - If `τ > t`, then for `s ≤ t < τ`, `X_s^τ = X_s`, so `sup_{s ≤ t} ‖X_s^τ‖ = sup_{s ≤ t} ‖X_s‖ ≤ K` (since no `s ≤ t` can have `‖X_s‖ ≥ K` because `τ > t` is the first such time).\n\nBut there are some holes:\n- We assumed that if `τ = ⊤`, then `‖X_s‖ < K` for all `s`. If not, `τ` should not be `⊤`. \n   So perhaps `hittingAfter` is undefined if `K` is never reached, but Lean might not care.\n\n### Abstract Proof Sketch\n\n1. **Assume `hittingAfter` is defined so that**:\n   - If there exists `s` such that `‖X_s‖ ≥ K`, then `τ = inf {s | ‖X_s‖ ≥ K}` (first such `s`).\n   - Otherwise, `τ = ⊤`.\n   - If `‖X_⊥‖ ≥ K`, then `τ = ⊥`.\n\n2. **Consider two cases**:\n   - **Case 1**: `τ = ⊤`.\n     - Then for all `s`, `‖X_s‖ < K`.\n     - Thus, the LHS `sup_{s ≤ t} ‖X_s^τ‖ = sup_{s ≤ t} ‖X_s‖ < K`, and the RHS is `K`, so LHS ≤ RHS.\n   - **Case 2**: `τ ≠ ⊤`.\n     - **Subcase 2.1**: `τ ≤ t`.\n       - For `s < τ`, `‖X_s‖ < K`, and `X_s^τ = X_s`, so `‖X_s^τ‖ < K`.\n       - For `s = τ`, `X_s^τ = X_τ`, so `‖X_s^τ‖ ≥ K`.\n       - For `s > τ`, `X_s^τ = X_τ`, same as `s = τ`.\n       - The supremum is `≥ K`, and the RHS is `K + ‖X_τ‖ ≥ K + K ≥ K`.\n         But actually, the supremum is at most `‖X_τ‖`, because all `s < τ` are `< K`, and `s ≥ τ` are `≤ ‖X_τ‖`.\n         No: for `s ≥ τ`, `X_s^τ = X_τ`, but if `s < τ`, it's `X_s`. \n         It's messy, and the inequality is `sup ≤ K + ‖X_τ‖`. \n         But `X_s^τ = X_s` for `s < τ` (but `‖X_s‖ < K`), and for `s ≥ τ`, it is `X_τ` (`≥ K`).\n         So the supremum is `max(sup_{s < τ} ‖X_s‖, ‖X_τ‖) ≤ max(K, ‖X_τ‖) ≤ K + ‖X_τ‖`.\n         But this is not tight: we should have `sup_{s < τ} ‖X_s‖ < K` and `‖X_τ‖ ≥ K`, so `sup = ‖X_τ‖`, and `‖X_τ‖ ≤ K + ‖X_τ‖`.\n     - **Subcase 2.2**: `τ > t`.\n       - For all `s ≤ t`, `s < τ`, so `X_s^τ = X_s`, and `‖X_s‖ < K`.\n       - Thus, LHS `sup_{s ≤ t} ‖X_s‖ < K`, and RHS is `K + 0 = K`.\n\nBut looking back, in **Case 2.1**, when `τ ≤ t`, we have `sup ≤ ‖X_τ‖` (since `X_s ≤ X_τ` for `s ≥ τ`?), and `‖X_τ‖ = K + ‖X_τ‖ - K ≤ K + ‖X_τ‖`.\n\nBut perhaps the Lean problem is using `‖X_s^τ‖ ≤ K + 1_{τ ≤ t} ‖X_τ‖`, which is likely correct (because if `τ ≤ t`, `X_s^τ = X_s if s < τ, X_τ if s ≥ τ`, and `‖X_s^τ‖ ≤ max(K, ‖X_τ‖) ≤ K + ‖X_τ‖`; and if `τ > t`, `X_s^τ = X_s`, and `‖X_s‖ < K`). \n\nHowever, Lean uses `⨆ s, ⨆ (_ : s ≤ t), ‖X_s^τ‖`, which is `sup_{s ≤ t} ‖X_s^τ‖`.\n\nGiven that, let's assume that for every `s ≤ t`, `‖X_s^τ‖ ≤ K + 1_{τ ≤ t} ‖X_τ‖`, and then take the supremum over `s ≤ t` to get the result. \n\nBut for a fixed `s ≤ t`, is `‖X_s^τ‖ ≤ K + 1_{τ ≤ t} ‖X_τ‖`? \n\nYes:\n- If `τ > t ≥ s`, then `X_s^τ = X_s`, and `τ > t` implies no `s ≤ t` has `‖X_s‖ ≥ K`, so `‖X_s‖ < K ≤ K + 0`.\n- If `τ ≤ t`, and",
